      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Daily sales aggregation\n",
        "daily_sales_query = \"\"\"\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        DATE(`Order Date`) as order_date,\n",
        "        SUM(Sales) as daily_sales\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        `mgmt599-emmanuel-opoku-lab1.pipeline_processed_data.superstore_transformed`\n",
        "    GROUP BY 1\n",
        "    ORDER BY 1\n",
        "\"\"\"\n",
        "daily_sales_df = client.query(daily_sales_query).to_dataframe()\n",
        "print(\"Daily Sales Aggregation:\")\n",
        "display(daily_sales_df.head())\n",
        "\n",
        "# Weekly sales aggregation\n",
        "weekly_sales_query = \"\"\"\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        DATE_TRUNC(DATE(`Order Date`), WEEK) as order_week,\n",
        "        SUM(Sales) as weekly_sales\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        `mgmt599-emmanuel-opoku-lab1.pipeline_processed_data.superstore_transformed`\n",
        "    GROUP BY 1\n",
        "    ORDER BY 1\n",
        "\"\"\"\n",
        "weekly_sales_df = client.query(weekly_sales_query).to_dataframe()\n",
        "print(\"\\nWeekly Sales Aggregation:\")\n",
        "display(weekly_sales_df.head())\n",
        "\n",
        "# Monthly sales aggregation\n",
        "monthly_sales_query = \"\"\"\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        DATE_TRUNC(DATE(`Order Date`), MONTH) as order_month,\n",
        "        SUM(Sales) as monthly_sales\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        `mgmt599-emmanuel-opoku-lab1.pipeline_processed_data.superstore_transformed`\n",
        "    GROUP BY 1\n",
        "    ORDER BY 1\n",
        "\"\"\"\n",
        "monthly_sales_df = client.query(monthly_sales_query).to_dataframe()\n",
        "print(\"\\nMonthly Sales Aggregation:\")\n",
        "display(monthly_sales_df.head())\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Daily sales with moving averages and anomalies\n",
        "daily_sales_analysis_query = \"\"\"\n",
        "    WITH DailySales AS (\n",
        "        SELECT\n",
        "            DATE(`Order Date`) as order_date,\n",
        "            SUM(Sales) as daily_sales\n",
        "        FROM\n",
        "            `mgmt599-emmanuel-opoku-lab1.pipeline_processed_data.superstore_transformed`\n",
        "        GROUP BY 1\n",
        "    ),\n",
        "    MovingAverages AS (\n",
        "        SELECT\n",
        "            order_date,\n",
        "            daily_sales,\n",
        "            AVG(daily_sales) OVER (ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN 6 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) as moving_avg_7day,\n",
        "            AVG(daily_sales) OVER (ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) as moving_avg_30day,\n",
        "            AVG(daily_sales) OVER (ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) - 2 * STDDEV(daily_sales) OVER (ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) as lower_bound,\n",
        "            AVG(daily_sales) OVER (ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) + 2 * STDDEV(daily_sales) OVER (ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) as upper_bound\n",
        "        FROM DailySales\n",
        "    )\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        order_date,\n",
        "        daily_sales,\n",
        "        moving_avg_7day,\n",
        "        moving_avg_30day,\n",
        "        CASE\n",
        "            WHEN daily_sales < lower_bound OR daily_sales > upper_bound THEN 'Anomaly'\n",
        "            ELSE 'Normal'\n",
        "        END as anomaly_flag\n",
        "    FROM MovingAverages\n",
        "    ORDER BY order_date\n",
        "\"\"\"\n",
        "daily_sales_analysis_df = client.query(daily_sales_analysis_query).to_dataframe()\n",
        "print(\"\\nDaily Sales with Moving Averages and Anomaly Flag:\")\n",
        "display(daily_sales_analysis_df.head())\n",
        "\n",
        "# Note: Identifying trend and seasonality components directly in a single SQL query is complex\n",
        "# and often requires more advanced statistical methods or libraries outside of SQL.\n",
        "# For a full time series decomposition, you would typically use libraries like statsmodels in Python\n",
        "# after extracting the data."

        "cohort_analysis_query = \"\"\"\n",
        "WITH CustomerFirstPurchase AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        `Customer ID`,\n",
        "        MIN(DATE_TRUNC(DATE(`Order Date`), MONTH)) as first_purchase_month\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        `mgmt599-emmanuel-opoku-lab1.pipeline_processed_data.superstore_transformed`\n",
        "    GROUP BY\n",
        "        `Customer ID`\n",
        "),\n",
        "CohortSales AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        cfp.first_purchase_month,\n",
        "        DATE_TRUNC(DATE(t.`Order Date`), MONTH) as purchase_month,\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT t.`Customer ID`) as monthly_customers,\n",
        "        SUM(t.Sales) as monthly_revenue\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        `mgmt599-emmanuel-opoku-lab1.pipeline_processed_data.superstore_transformed` as t\n",
        "    JOIN\n",
        "        CustomerFirstPurchase as cfp ON t.`Customer ID` = cfp.`Customer ID`\n",
        "    GROUP BY\n",
        "        1, 2\n",
        "),\n",
        "CohortMetrics AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        first_purchase_month,\n",
        "        purchase_month,\n",
        "        EXTRACT(YEAR FROM purchase_month) * 12 + EXTRACT(MONTH FROM purchase_month) - (EXTRACT(YEAR FROM first_purchase_month) * 12 + EXTRACT(MONTH FROM first_purchase_month)) as cohort_age_months,\n",
        "        monthly_customers,\n",
        "        monthly_revenue\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        CohortSales\n",
        "),\n",
        "CohortSize AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        first_purchase_month,\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT `Customer ID`) as total_cohort_customers\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        CustomerFirstPurchase\n",
        "    GROUP BY\n",
        "        1\n",
        ")\n",
        "SELECT\n",
        "    cm.first_purchase_month,\n",
        "    cm.cohort_age_months,\n",
        "    cs.total_cohort_customers,\n",
        "    cm.monthly_customers,\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(cm.monthly_customers, cs.total_cohort_customers) as retention_rate,\n",
        "    cm.monthly_revenue,\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(cm.monthly_revenue, cm.monthly_customers) as average_purchase_value,\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(cm.monthly_revenue, cs.total_cohort_customers) as revenue_per_customer\n",
        "FROM\n",
        "    CohortMetrics as cm\n",
        "JOIN\n",
        "    CohortSize as cs ON cm.first_purchase_month = cs.first_purchase_month\n",
        "ORDER BY\n",
        "    cm.first_purchase_month, cm.cohort_age_months\n",
        "\"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "cohort_analysis_df = client.query(cohort_analysis_query).to_dataframe()\n",

        "product_association_query = \"\"\"\n",
        "WITH OrderProducts AS (\n",
        "    SELECT DISTINCT\n",
        "        `Order ID`,\n",
        "        `Product Name`,\n",
        "        Sales\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        `mgmt599-emmanuel-opoku-lab1.pipeline_processed_data.superstore_transformed`\n",
        "),\n",
        "ProductPairs AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        op1.`Order ID`,\n",
        "        op1.`Product Name` as product_a,\n",
        "        op2.`Product Name` as product_b,\n",
        "        op1.Sales as sales_a,\n",
        "        op2.Sales as sales_b\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        OrderProducts op1\n",
        "    JOIN\n",
        "        OrderProducts op2 ON op1.`Order ID` = op2.`Order ID` AND op1.`Product Name` < op2.`Product Name`\n",
        "),\n",
        "PairCounts AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        product_a,\n",
        "        product_b,\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT `Order ID`) as pair_count,\n",
        "        SUM(sales_a + sales_b) as pair_revenue\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        ProductPairs\n",
        "    GROUP BY 1, 2\n",
        "),\n",
        "ProductCounts AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        `Product Name`,\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT `Order ID`) as product_count\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        OrderProducts\n",
        "    GROUP BY 1\n",
        "),\n",
        "TotalOrders AS (\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT `Order ID`) as total_orders\n",
        "    FROM\n",
        "        OrderProducts\n",
        ")\n",
        "SELECT\n",
        "    pc.product_a,\n",
        "    pc.product_b,\n",
        "    pc.pair_count,\n",
        "    pa.product_count as product_a_count,\n",
        "    pb.product_count as product_b_count,\n",
        "    t.total_orders, -- Changed alias from 'to' to 't'\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(pc.pair_count, t.total_orders) as support, -- Changed alias from 'to' to 't'\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(pc.pair_count, pa.product_count) as confidence_a_to_b,\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(pc.pair_count, pb.product_count) as confidence_b_to_a,\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(SAFE_DIVIDE(pc.pair_count, pa.product_count), SAFE_DIVIDE(pb.product_count, t.total_orders)) as lift_a_to_b, -- Changed alias from 'to' to 't'\n",
        "    SAFE_DIVIDE(SAFE_DIVIDE(pc.pair_count, pb.product_count), SAFE_DIVIDE(pa.product_count, t.total_orders)) as lift_b_to_a, -- Changed alias from 'to' to 't'\n",
        "    pc.pair_revenue\n",
        "FROM\n",
        "    PairCounts pc\n",
        "JOIN\n",
        "    ProductCounts pa ON pc.product_a = pa.`Product Name`\n",
        "JOIN\n",
        "    ProductCounts pb ON pc.product_b = pb.`Product Name`\n",
        "CROSS JOIN\n",
        "    TotalOrders t -- Changed alias from 'to' to 't'\n",
        "ORDER BY\n",
        "    support DESC\n",
        "LIMIT 20\n",

        "# SQL Analysis Results\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook performed several SQL-based analyses on the \\`superstore_transformed\\` dataset in BigQuery, complemented by some Python-based analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 1. Time Series Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "**Objective:** Analyze sales trends over time, including daily, weekly, and monthly aggregations, moving averages, and anomaly detection.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Methodology:**\n",
        "- Used BigQuery SQL to aggregate sales data by day, week, and month.\n",
        "- Calculated 7-day and 30-day moving averages for daily sales using window functions in BigQuery SQL.\n",
        "- Identified sales anomalies as data points falling outside two standard deviations from the 30-day moving average.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Findings:** The time series analysis provided insights into the daily, weekly, and monthly sales trends. The moving averages helped smooth out daily fluctuations, and the anomaly detection flagged days with unusually high or low sales, which could warrant further investigation.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 2. Customer Cohort Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "**Objective:** Analyze customer behavior over time by grouping customers based on their first purchase month (cohort). Track retention, average purchase value, and revenue contribution by cohort age.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Methodology:**\n",
        "- Used BigQuery SQL with CTEs to:\n",
        "    - Identify the first purchase month for each customer (\\`CustomerFirstPurchase\\`).\n",
        "    - Aggregate monthly sales and customer counts by first purchase month and subsequent purchase months (\\`CohortSales\\`).\n",
        "    - Calculate the cohort age in months (\\`CohortMetrics\\`).\n",
        "    - Determine the initial size of each cohort (\\`CohortSize\\`).\n",
        "- Joined the CTEs to calculate retention rate, average purchase value, and revenue per customer by cohort age.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Findings:** The cohort analysis allows tracking the behavior of customer groups acquired at different times. Metrics like retention rate and revenue per customer by cohort age provide insights into customer loyalty and the long-term value of different customer cohorts. The cohort analysis DataFrame has 894 rows.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3. Product Association Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "**Objective:** Identify products frequently purchased together and calculate association rule metrics (support, confidence, lift) and revenue impact.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Methodology:**\n",
        "- Used a BigQuery SQL query with CTEs to:\n",
        "    - Get distinct products per order (\\`OrderProducts\\`).\n",
        "    - Generate all unique pairs of products within the same order (\\`ProductPairs\\`).\n",
        "    - Count the occurrences and calculate the total revenue for each product pair (\\`PairCounts\\`).\n",
        "    - Count the total orders for each individual product (\\`ProductCounts\\`).\n",
        "    - Get the total number of unique orders in the dataset (\\`TotalOrders\\`).\n",
        "- Joined the CTEs to calculate support, confidence, and lift for each product pair, and included the pair revenue.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Findings:** The product association analysis identified pairs of products frequently bought together, along with metrics like support, confidence, and lift. These insights can be valuable for merchandising, recommendations, and promotional strategies. The \\`pair_count\\` column indicates how many times each pair appeared together in an order. For the displayed top 20 pairs, the \\`pair_count\\` was 2."
